Hydraulic capacity should be at least consistent with the existing watercourse and able to accept a 1 in 100 year flood flows plus an assessment for climate change (an additional 20%). 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \s18 \rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f3\lang2057\langfe1033\langfenp1033\insrsid5596484\charrsid5596484 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}
The Soffit level of the bridge should be set 600mm above the maximum flood water level to allow clearance from debris and wave action, and a further 300mm to allow for changes in water level due to climate change. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \s18 \rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f3\lang2057\langfe1033\langfenp1033\insrsid5596484\charrsid5596484 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}
The bridge should not cause flooding either at the site or upstream and downstream of the site. Afflux backwater effect should be kept to a minimum and in all cases must not exceed 75 mm. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\ltrpar \s18 \rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \f3\lang2057\langfe1033\langfenp1033\insrsid5596484\charrsid5596484 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}
The abutments should be set back from brink of bank to allow for maintenance and improvement works and provide suitable space to allow mammals to pass. 
